    <!-- Application Structure Plan: The application is structured as a single-page, vertically scrolling educational guide. This linear, top-to-bottom flow is intuitive for users learning a new topic. It starts with a general introduction, then logically progresses through the core tools of IR: needles, wires, and catheters/sheaths. Key concepts like the French scale are given their own dedicated, interactive sections to ensure comprehension. The structure uses a single-column layout for mobile and a two-column grid for larger screens in specific sections to present related text and visuals side-by-side, enhancing understanding. The primary interaction is scrolling, supplemented by interactive calculators and clickable tabs, which allow users to explore specific data points without leaving the flow of the page. This design avoids complex navigation, making it ideal for presenting foundational knowledge clearly and accessibly. -->
    <!-- Visualization & Content Choices: 
        - Report Info: Needle Gauge Sizes -> Goal: Compare -> Viz/Presentation: Interactive Bar Chart (Chart.js) -> Interaction: Hover to see exact mm values. -> Justification: A bar chart provides an immediate visual comparison of outer diameters, which is more impactful than a simple table. The interactivity on hover gives precise data without cluttering the initial view.
        - Report Info: French Scale -> Goal: Explain -> Viz/Presentation: Interactive Calculator (HTML/JS) -> Interaction: User inputs French size, sees mm equivalent. -> Justification: An interactive tool engages the user and solidifies their understanding of the conversion (Fr/3 = mm) far better than static text.
        - Report Info: Sheath vs. Catheter Sizing -> Goal: Clarify Difference -> Viz/Presentation: Diagram using HTML/CSS/Tailwind -> Interaction: Side-by-side visual comparison with explanatory text updated by JS. -> Justification: A visual diagram is essential to explain the concept that a sheath's French size refers to its inner diameter while a catheter's refers to its outer. This is a common point of confusion that a static description alone cannot easily resolve.
        - Report Info: Catheter Types -> Goal: Organize/Inform -> Viz/Presentation: Tabbed content cards (HTML/CSS/JS) -> Interaction: Clicking a catheter name reveals its image and description. -> Justification: A tabbed interface organizes a large amount of information compactly. It allows users to focus on one catheter type at a time, preventing information overload and making the content easily digestible.
    -->
    <!-- CONFIRMATION: NO SVG graphics used. NO Mermaid JS used. -->
